messages.content:
ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:23` frees `b->name` on the recoverable parse-error path but leaves the dangling pointer stored in the returned `blob_t`. The caller later calls `destroy_blob()` (`program.c:42`), which unconditionally frees `b->name` again at `program.c:33`, causing the AddressSanitizer double-free. GDB confirmed that at entry to `destroy_blob`, `b->size == 0` and `b->name` still points at the previously freed allocation (`0x502000000030`).

LOCAL FIX: After `free(b->name)` in `load_blob()`’s recoverable error path, immediately set `b->name = NULL;` before returning. Since `free(NULL)` is safe, `destroy_blob()` can then be called normally without double-freeing. For example:
```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);
    b->name = NULL;
    b->size = 0;
    return b;
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Make ownership/state invariants explicit and enforce them throughout the API: any pointer field in a live object must either be a valid owned allocation or `NULL`, never dangling. A structural improvement would be to centralize cleanup through a single destructor/clear helper, e.g. `blob_clear(blob_t *)`, that frees and nulls owned fields, and have all error paths use it. Alternatively redesign `load_blob()` so recoverable parse errors do not return partially initialized owning objects—return an error/status code separately from the output object, or return `NULL` plus an error enum—so ownership transfer is unambiguous.

